{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte** defines *liberté* (liberty) precisely as \"the state of a person who encounters, in his fellow men, no obstacle, whether to the regular development of his being, or to the innocent exercise of his faculties.\"[^1] Its strongest principle opposes slavery's core tenet that one man can possess another: \"a man can never be legitimately possessed by another, and that the products of his labors belong only to him, so long as he has not freely alienated them.\"[^2] He contrasts slavery's regime—where masters direct labor, restrict movement, arms, association, education, and hold unaccountable power—with liberty's, where society protects the weak, individuals choose occupations, move freely, associate, educate their children, elect agents, demand accountability, and judge actions by universal human consequences.[^3]\n\nComte would consider property insecurity an unmet condition: as long as any man or state can seize labor's fruits without consent (treating persons as \"things\"), or masters live idly off slaves' toil, true liberty remains negated, blocking rights/duties like self-development and mutual respect.[^4]\n\n**Allama Iqbal** invokes *aazadi* (freedom) poetically, often as lost natural/spiritual autonomy or communal revival. A bird laments its cage: \"Those garden splendors, the chorus of all, / The freedom to come and to go at my call,\" symbolizing captivity's ache.[^5] In *Visal*, paradoxical self-liberation emerges: \"By entering chains, I found my liberty, / My home was built upon the wreck of me,\" tying freedom to divine surrender beyond worldly bonds.[^6] The Eid crescent witnesses Muslims \"prisoners in sectarianism's chains,\" contrasting its own \"freedom,\" underscoring disunity's enslavement.[^7]\n\nIqbal would deem spiritual/national disunity an unmet condition: without *khudi* (selfhood), revival from godlessness, sectarianism, and colonial mimicry, freedom devolves to mere \"liberties\" like Western education's hollow solace, failing Islamic renaissance.[^8]\n\nComte's *liberté* is economic/political—no coerced labor, secure property enabling individual duties. Iqbal's *aazadi* is dynamic self-assertion, communal/spiritual liberation from inner chains toward ummah renewal.\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, [Chapter 3](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/03-de-ce-qui-constitue-la-liberte/translation/#p-1c5676).\n\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, [Chapter 3](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/03-de-ce-qui-constitue-la-liberte/translation/#p-86c544).\n\n[^3]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, [Chapter 3](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/03-de-ce-qui-constitue-la-liberte/translation/).\n\n[^4]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, [Chapter 2](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/02-de-la-liberte-consideree-comme-une-condition-de-le/translation/#p-2cd7a3); [Chapter 3](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/03-de-ce-qui-constitue-la-liberte/translation/#p-0a1986).\n\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [Chapter 34](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/34-parinde-ki-faryad/translation/#p-c41448).\n\n[^6]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [Chapter 27](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/27-visal/translation/#p-456772).\n\n[^7]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [Chapter 8](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/08-ghurra-e/translation/#p-37e39f).\n\n[^8]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [Chapter 22](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/22-taleem-aur-iske-nataaij/translation/#p-c70195).",
